<%# locals: (notable:, parent: nil, note: nil) %>
<%# MiClassrooms Phase 5 Task 7 (Brief §14.1, D15): one form partial serves
    three contexts — a top-level create (parent/note nil), a reply create
    (parent: the root being replied to), and an in-place edit (note: the
    persisted record). `record` below picks the right target/verb for each;
    `form.rich_text_area :body` is Lexxy's editor (config/application.rb
    wires Rails' own ActionText editor adapter to Lexxy — no special helper
    name needed).

    This partial itself carries NO id for a NEW record: the CALLER wraps it
    in a spacing <div id="..."> (notes/_list.html.erb's `_new_note` divs,
    notes/_note.html.erb's `_new_reply` div), and that div's id is the exact
    string NotesController#reset_target_for computes (dom_id(notable,
    :new_note) for a root create, dom_id(parent, :new_reply) for a reply).
    Giving this form the SAME id as its wrapping div would be a duplicate id
    (invalid HTML, and `getElementById`/turbo_stream targeting would resolve
    to the div instead of the form) — so after a successful create, the
    controller's turbo_stream response does `turbo_stream.update(reset_target,
    ...)`, which replaces the wrapping div's INNER content with a freshly
    rendered (blank) copy of this same partial while the div itself (and its
    mt-3/mt-2 spacing) stays put, resetting the form for the actor without
    disturbing the wrapper a second submission still needs. An edit form
    needs no such id: Note's own broadcast_replace_to swaps the ENTIRE note
    (this form included) back to read mode for every subscriber, actor
    included.

    Whole-branch review I-1 (WCAG 2.2 AAA): `form_with model: record` derives
    its field ids from `record.model_name.param_key`, which is "note" for a
    Note whether new OR persisted — so without help, every context below
    (top-level create, each root note's reply form, each note's inline edit
    form) would emit the SAME `note_body` field id, and every
    `form.label :body` would resolve to the FIRST one in document order.
    `namespace:` prefixes every field id (and the label's `for`, computed the
    same way) with a per-context string — reusing the exact id each
    context's own CONTAINER already uses above the form (the create/reply
    wrapper div's id, or the note's own li id for an edit), so it's
    guaranteed unique per context without inventing a second id scheme. This
    only changes generated FIELD ids: it never touches submitted param names
    (still note[body], note[alert], …) nor any container/broadcast target
    id (dom_id(notable)_notes, dom_id(note)_replies, dom_id(note) are
    computed independently in notes/_list.html.erb and notes/_note.html.erb
    and are untouched by this). %>
<%
  record = note || Note.new(notable: notable, parent: parent)
  persisted = record.persisted?
  url = persisted ? note_path(record) : notes_path
  namespace = if persisted
                dom_id(record)
  elsif parent
                dom_id(parent, :new_reply)
  else
                dom_id(notable, :new_note)
  end
  submit_label = if persisted
                   t("notes.form.update_submit")
  elsif parent
                   t("notes.form.reply_submit")
  else
                   t("notes.form.create_submit")
  end
%>
<%= form_with model: record, url: url, method: (persisted ? :patch : :post),
      namespace: namespace, class: "space-y-3" do |form| %>
  <%= form.error_summary %>
  <%= form.hidden_field :notable_type, value: notable.class.name %>
  <%= form.hidden_field :notable_id, value: notable.id %>
  <% if parent %>
    <%= form.hidden_field :parent_id, value: parent.id %>
  <% end %>

  <div class="space-y-2">
    <%= form.label :body, t("notes.form.body_label"), class: "block text-sm font-medium text-text-body" %>
    <%= form.rich_text_area :body %>
  </div>

  <%= form.check_box :alert, label: t("notes.form.alert_label") %>

  <%= form.submit submit_label %>
<% end %>
